If you look you will find countless stories of bolt and/or carriers made by some new companies that have popped up and even some well known brands that used other than normal suppliers or rushed through the quality control process and having catastrophic failures. This is one part you don't want to take a chance on over saving $25 or $50. Spikes Tactical BCGs are of the highest quality available and not only meet but exceed milspec requirements by far, as well as carry a lifetime warranty. $200 cash, shipping is available. Spikes BCGs are known to be one of the best on the market, hands down. They are marked HPT/MPI, have a great phosphate finish, and have the Spikes Spider logo laser engraved on it and visible through the ejection port door. The carrier is made from 8620 tool steel, and the bolt is CNC machined from Carpenter #158. They are each individually high pressure tested and then magnetically particle inspected, not batch tested as many brands are. Full specifications are listed below.


Bolt carrier group specifications-

-Mil-Spec 8620 tool steel M16 bolt carrier w/shrouded firing pin.

-Carrier has 5.3.1.2 MIL-STD-171 phosphate finish inside and out with 1.2.2.2 MIL-STD-171 hard chrome bore.

-Carrier key is attached with Grade 8 hardware and properly staked per the Mil-Spec.

-Bolts are CNC machined from Carpenter No. 158®.

-Bolts have 5.3.1.2 MIL-STD-171 phosphate finish inside and out.

-All bolts are shot peened per the current Mil-Spec.

-All bolts are Individually High Pressure Tested (HPT) and then Individually Magnetic Particle Inspected (MPI).

-Tool steel extractor, shot peened, 5.3.1.2 MIL-STD-171 phosphate finish, fitted with a Mil-Spec black extractor spring insert and Mil-Spec Viton o-ring.

For Sale:  870 Tactical Magpul Full Nickel Boron Custom
postcontent: This shotgun began life as a new Remington 870 12 Gauge Tactical Express. Fluvanna Ordnance is a veteran owned company, and have experience through multiple tours in Iraq and Afghanistan utilizing this platform. Mass production has led to poor tolerances, parts that simply do not meet muster, and a gun that was a shadow of what the 870 once was. For three months we modified and tested our R&D 870, until finally what we felt was perfection was achieved. One of the primary goals being able to use an optic or tritium bead, and not have it “Figure 8” when charging the next shell. After careful analysis we found all the key friction points to accomplish the smoothest cycling possible from a pump shotgun. The ramps on the charging handle have been re-worked and smoothed to pass the springs in the receiver more efficiently. The Bolt has been smoothed to glass on the bottom, the bolt internals completely re-worked to get a fluid relationship between them and the follower. The bolt follower has been smoothed and polished, the sharp angles worked into a smooth radius and polished and all imperfections from casting re-worked and polished. All the parts of the trigger group have been re-worked and polished meticulously, until the feedback from the trigger pull was smooth and precise. Simply put, the operator will know exactly when the shot will be released, unlike originally where a firm pull was required throwing the gun slightly off target, now a gentle squeeze is all that is required; and the operator knows precisely when the shot will come. After completion of all the modifications, the Receiver/Charging Handle/Barrel/Shell Tube/Billet Shell Follower/Bolt/Bolt Internals and Bolt Follower were all coated In Nickel Boron X; and all parts listed except the bolt internals/follower/shell follower coated with a High-Heat Ceramic that has many attributes. The looks and durability are bar none the finest, heat dissipation is vastly improved, and it can be painted to adapt to varying environments if need be, and stripped easily without taking the ceramic coating off. The buffer adaptor is also ceramic coated. The trigger, QD sockets, shell saddles, big-dome safeties, rails, barrel clamp, weapon light rail, castle nut, buffer lock plate, shell door and every single bolt have had Cerakote applied. We took it to the level of Cerakoting every bolt as they are now completely corrosion proof. This model has Quick Disconnect sling attachment points, or 5 if the weapon light rail is removed. The weapon light rail can be swapped to either the left or right side depending on Operator preference as well. Once the function had been properly attended to, form was given the next highest priority. Almost every part is done in contrast to the surrounding parts, creating a vivid portrait of the attention to detail involved in these builds. These are truly works of flawlessly functional art, and honestly may never be taken to this level again except by special request, as the time involved surpassed anything we expected initially. Our gunsmiths and designers are perfectionists, so until what we felt was perfection was achieved we did not stop. This build utilizes a Mesa Tactical High-Mount buffer adaptor and Enidine hydraulic buffer assembly, mitigating recoil by 70%. A load of 00 Buck shot produces just over 600 foot pounds of felt recoil, with this setup that is reduced to just over 200 foot pounds of felt recoil. There are other similar systems on the market, but the Enidine marketed by Mesa is the finest and guaranteed for 2 million cycles. Utilizing M4/AR 15 collapsible butt-stocks and grips are made possible by this system as well. This build utilizes the Magpul MOE forend, Magpul MOE grip, Magpul ACS-L Stock

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson M500 Silver 8 3/8" - Tanaka
location: New Jersey, New Jersey, United States
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson M500 Silver 8 3/8" - Tanaka

I just want to sell it out, that's why am selling it cheaper, you can never know what you are getting for this cheap not until you get a hold of it.

The 500 is unusual amongst Tanaka revolvers in that there is no gas nozzle/adaptor to allow you to extend the fill nozzle on a gas can to reach the cylinder mounted gas nozzle. This is because the 500's cylinder is so large in diameter that a gas can's nozzle can align directly with the cylinder simply swung out.

BIG. There is no other word for it.

The gun is truly huge, dwarfing the M29 and even the mighty Desert Eagle.

Some statistics - Length 15", Cylinder length 2.25", real steel weight 2kg...

However, you do not get the sense of how big it is just from these photographs because everything is to scale. The frame has to be massive, because the cylinder (only holding 5 rounds and there are 5 fake rounds in there) is so vast.

The Rubber Hogue like grips, however, look a little odd, because S&W (and Tanaka, by copying it) made them in the same dimensions as the K frame revolvers, like the model 19 .357 magnum, a whole frame size smaller than the old .44,

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson M500 Silver 8 3/8" - Tanaka
location: New York - buffalo, Buffalo, New York
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson M500 Silver 8 3/8" - Tanaka

I just want to sell it out, that's why am selling it cheaper, you can never know what you are getting for this cheap not until you get a hold of it.

The 500 is unusual amongst Tanaka revolvers in that there is no gas nozzle/adaptor to allow you to extend the fill nozzle on a gas can to reach the cylinder mounted gas nozzle. This is because the 500's cylinder is so large in diameter that a gas can's nozzle can align directly with the cylinder simply swung out.
First Impressions

BIG. There is no other word for it.

The gun is truly huge, dwarfing the M29 and even the mighty Desert Eagle.

title: For Sale:  .22lr
postcontent:
I just wanted to put out a message to everyone thinking of buying ammo off of this site. Don't. Just, do not support the disgusting practices that are being carried out on this site. When you see someone selling .22lr for $0.20-.30 a round, or .22 for $1 per round, DON'T TALK TO THESE PEOPLE, DO NOT BUY ANYTHING FROM THEM.
These people are the largest reason that ammo is so difficult to find right now. They go down to the store at 6am, buy every single box they can (even if they have a 1 box limit. These people are scammers, they know how to get around it.) then immediately come onto Armslist, and sell it foe $50 a box. This is truly disgusting that people do this. I understand that everyone wants to try and turn a quick buck now and again, but the way this is going has got to stop. This hobby is a truly wonderful one, but we need to support each other during this shortage. We cannot support these people and their practices.

If you want to be able to enjoy this hobby and be able to find ammo, we all need to vote with our wallets, and vote these people out with their hoarding and overpriced ammo.

title: For Sale:  AAC Tirant 45 Suppressor .45ACP - Take Apart Version
postcontent:
Sadly, a job relocation may be on the horizon to a state where NFA items are not allowed. Its BS but what are ya gonna do....

As such, I am looking to sell my AAC Tirant 45 Suppressor to a PA resident. The can has about 250 rounds through it and was painstakingly cleaned after every trip to the range. Zero issues with the can, absolutely no baffle strikes or any problems. It is truly awesome to listen to it. Potential buyers can demo the can with me at a local range if so desired to hear its awesomeness. I have multiple pistons for different thread types and calibers which I will also include (a $200 value) if I don't sell them first.

If you wish to proceed to purchase, you must be a PA resident, at least 21 years of age, have an absolutely pristine criminal background, know the type of transfer that makes sense for you (individual, Trust, LLC/Corp), and be willing to wait 6 months for ATF to process your paperwork before you can take delivery.

Here is the process:
1.) Pay for the item ($500 to me, the seller)
2.) I will complete with you the form 4's and US Citizenship form 
3.) Get 2 passport photos taken from Walgreens or CVS and attach them to the Form 4
4.) Get your county's Chief Law Enforcement Officer (CLEO) to sign off on your Form 4 (not needed for trust or LLC/Corp route, only individual transfer). At the same time, your CLEO signs off on your form they will also do your fingerprints cards which go up with the Form 4.
6.) Write a $200 personal or cashiers check made out to the BAFTE
5.) Together, we will double check your forms & cards, then I mail them along with your $200 Check to the ATF (total cost to you is $750 all in) I paid over $1000 all in FYI.
6.) Wait 6 months for the ATF to process your paperwork
7.) One of the best days of your life comes when you get a call from me saying that your Form 4 came back with the tax stamp approved by the ATF for you to own the item. After we hang up, come over and pick up your suppressor and have a great life!
